<subSubSection id="A2C5BF3EC17B748E10F0EA5038052F7B" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="notes">
<paragraph id="275D04AF6D986094379E0D8D5B799B15" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="28CBA1B94C34FF708BFEF2A98C5A651E" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
This species appears to be related to 
<taxonomicName id="2E8CE75D9B818103805A2C4AFE29A5F1" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Ipomoea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="sericosepala">
<emphasis id="9CCAF731CFAC515C860BDC1FE3A02156" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Ipomoea sericosepala</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
because of the form of the inflorescence and the distribution of the indumentum on the corolla and almost all vegetative parts. It differs from 
<taxonomicName id="B1433713273403E2CBC89E446F5DB722" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Ipomoea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="sericosepala">
<emphasis id="42A46F28F4A6FA5168EEBDD693485E4F" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">I. sericosepala</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the distinctive velvety-grey indumentum and in the shape and size of the sepals which are subequal, ovate, 7-8 
<normalizedToken id="D94D7402D119A307C46045832AA52124" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
6-8 mm. It differs from all related species in the densely pubescent ovary.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="29EDB679E5FDA30E4A2EF0E3BE48F4DB" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Its placement here is unconfirmed.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
